  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Zero test infrastructure exists.** No `tests/` directory, no `pytest`/`unittest` files, no test dependencies in `requirements.txt`. Every module below is 0% covered. I'd recommend adding `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, and `respx` (for mocking `httpx`) as dev dependencies before starting.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — `parse_posted_at`, `Job`\n\n**Gaps**\n- Epoch-seconds vs epoch-milliseconds branch (`>=1e12` threshold) untested at the boundary.\n- Negative/garbage numeric strings (`\"-1\"`, `\"\"`, `None`-as-string).\n- ISO strings with/without `Z`, with/without offset, malformed ISO (`ValueError` path returning `None`).\n- `Job.key`, `content_hash` stability (same inputs → same hash; different `department` → different hash but same `key`).\n- `to_row()` drops `raw` and adds `key`/`content_hash`.\n- `posted_dt` property delegates correctly and returns `None` for bad data.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected\", [\n    (\"\", None),\n    (None, None),\n    (\"1643241332430\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # ms epoch\n    (\"1643241332\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),      # s epoch\n    (\"2022-01-26T22:15:32Z\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2022-01-26T22:15:32+00:00\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),\n    (\"2022-01-26T22:15:32\", datetime(2022, 1, 26, 22, 15, 32, tzinfo=timezone.utc)),  # naive -> UTC\n    (\"not a date\", None),\n    (\"Posted 3 Days Ago\", None),  # Workday prose, currently unparseable\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at(value, expected):\n    assert parse_posted_at(value) == expected\n\ndef test_job_key_stable_across_content_changes():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"A\", url=\"u\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"B\", url=\"u2\")\n    assert j1.key == j2.key\n    assert j1.content_hash != j2.content_hash\n\ndef test_to_row_excludes_raw_and_includes_computed_fields():\n    j = Job(source=\"lever\", company=\"x\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\", raw={\"x\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key\n    assert row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n\ndef test_posted_dt_property_delegates_to_parse_posted_at():\n    j = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\", posted_at=\"bad\")\n    assert j.posted_dt is None\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py` — `match`, `filter_jobs`\n\n**Gaps**\n- Word-boundary regex matching (`\\b`) — substring false positives/negatives (e.g. include `\"ai\"` shouldn't match `\"maintenance\"`, but should match `\"AI Engineer\"`).\n- Empty `include`/`exclude`/`locations` lists vs `None` (falsy check `if exclude:` — empty list and `None` behave identically, worth locking in).\n- Precedence: exclude wins over include when both match.\n- Location matching is substring + case-insensitive, not word-boundary — verify that's intentional and covered.\n- `cutoff` behavior: job with unparseable `posted_at` is **kept** (not dropped) even when cutoff set — this is a deliberate design decision worth a dedicated test so a future refactor doesn't accidentally start dropping unparseable dates.\n- `filter_jobs` with `max_age_days` as string vs int (`float(max_age)` cast).\n- `filter_jobs` with missing keys in `rules` dict (defaults via `.get`).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef make_job(**kw):\n    defaults = dict(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\",\n                     url=\"u\", department=\"\", location=\"\")\n    defaults.update(kw)\n    return Job(**defaults)\n\ndef test_include_word_boundary_no_substring_match():\n    j = make_job(title=\"Maintenance Tech\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"ai\"]) is False\n\ndef test_include_word_boundary_matches_whole_word():\n    j = make_job(title=\"AI Engineer\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"ai\"]) is True\n\ndef test_exclude_takes_precedence_over_include():\n    j = make_job(title=\"Senior AI Intern\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"ai\"], exclude=[\"intern\"]) is False\n\ndef test_location_substring_case_insensitive():\n    j = make_job(location=\"Remote - San Francisco, CA\")\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"san francisco\"]) is True\n    assert match(j, locations=[\"Austin\"]) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_confirmed_stale_job():\n    old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat()\n    j = make_job(posted_at=old)\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_job_with_unparseable_posted_at():\n    j = make_job(posted_at=\"Posted 3 Days Ago\")  # Workday prose, parse_posted_at -> None\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is True  # not dropped just because we can't confirm age\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_applies_max_age_days_as_string():\n    old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=10)).isoformat()\n    jobs = [make_job(posted_at=old)]\n    assert filter_jobs(jobs, {\"max_age_days\": \"5\"}) == []\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_empty_rules_returns_all():\n    jobs = [make_job(), make_job(external_id=\"2\")]\n    assert filter_jobs(jobs, {}) == jobs\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` — `Store` (SQLite dedup)\n\n**Gaps — the highest-value untested surface in the repo.**\n- `diff()`: new job insert, unchanged job (only `last_seen` bumped, no `changed`), changed job (`content_hash` differs → update + `changed`).\n- Schema migration path (`_migrate`): opening a pre-existing DB file that lacks `salary_range` column.\n- Context manager (`__enter__`/`__exit__`) closes connection.\n- `get_meta`/`set_meta`: missing key returns `None`; upsert overwrites existing value (`ON CONFLICT`).\n- `added_since`: ordering (`first_seen, company, title`), strict `>` boundary (a row with `first_seen == ts` must be excluded).\n- `count()` on empty vs populated DB.\n- Concurrent/second `diff()` call on the same jobs is idempotent (no duplicate rows, `first_seen` doesn't change on subsequent runs — only `last_seen`).\n- **No test for the migration actually altering an existing on-disk DB created before `salary_range` existed** — this is exactly the kind of regression a schema change could silently break.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport sqlite3\nimport pytest\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef job():\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\",\n                title=\"Engineer\", url=\"https://x\", location=\"NYC\")\n\ndef test_diff_inserts_new_job(tmp_path, job):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        new, changed = store.diff([job])\n        assert new == [job]\n        assert changed == []\n        assert store.count() == 1\n\ndef test_diff_unchanged_job_not_reported_as_changed(tmp_path, job):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        store.diff([job])\n        new, changed = store.diff([job])\n        assert new == [] and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_detects_content_change(tmp_path, job):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        store.diff([job])\n        updated = Job(**{**job.__dict__, \"title\": \"Senior Engineer\"})\n        new, changed = store.diff([updated])\n        assert new == []\n        assert changed == [updated]\n\ndef test_diff_first_seen_stable_across_runs(tmp_path, job):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        store.diff([job])\n        row1 = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs WHERE key=?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        store.diff([job])\n        row2 = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs WHERE key=?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        assert row1[\"first_seen\"] == row2[\"first_seen\"]\n\ndef test_migration_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_db(tmp_path):\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(str(path))\n    conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n        CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n          external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n          employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n          first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT);\n    \"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n    with Store(path) as store:\n        cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in store.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n        assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n\ndef test_get_set_meta_roundtrip_and_overwrite(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") is None\n        store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\"\n        store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"2026-02-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"2026-02-01T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_added_since_excludes_boundary_and_orders_correctly(tmp_path, job):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        store.diff([job])\n        ts = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[0]\n        assert store.added_since(ts) == []          # strict > excludes equal timestamp\n        assert len(store.added_since(\"2000-01-01T00:00:00\")) == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `pipeline.py` — `load_config`, `run`, `run_sync`\n\n**Gaps — no integration test at all for the orchestration path.**\n- `load_config`: defaults applied when keys missing (`sources`, `filters`, `db`, `concurrency`).\n- `run()` dry-run path: skips `Store`/`dispatch`, returns `{\"matched\", \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}`.\n- `run()` full path: verify `fetch_all` → `filter_jobs` → `store.diff` → `dispatch` call order, and that the returned dict counts match.\n- `run_sync` wraps `asyncio.run` correctly (can be tested by mocking `run`).\n- No test that an empty `sources.yaml` (0 sources) doesn't crash.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import AsyncMock, patch\nimport pipeline\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef test_load_config_applies_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(\"db: custom.db\\n\")\n    cfg = pipeline.load_config(cfg_file)\n    assert cfg[\"sources\"] == []\n    assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {}\n    assert cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n    assert cfg[\"db\"] == \"custom.db\"\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_dry_run_skips_store_and_dispatch(tmp_path):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n    job = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")\n    with patch(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", new=AsyncMock(return_value=[job])), \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.filter_jobs\", return_value=[job]), \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.Store\") as mock_store, \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.dispatch\") as mock_dispatch:\n        result = await pipeline.run(cfg_file, dry_run=True)\n    mock_store.assert_not_called()\n    mock_dispatch.assert_not_called()\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_full_path_persists_and_dispatches(tmp_path):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    job = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")\n    with patch(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", new=AsyncMock(return_value=[job])), \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.filter_jobs\", return_value=[job]), \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.dispatch\") as mock_dispatch:\n        result = await pipeline.run(cfg_file, dry_run=False)\n    assert result[\"new\"] == 1\n    mock_dispatch.assert_called_once()\n\ndef test_run_sync_invokes_asyncio_run(tmp_path):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n    with patch(\"pipeline.run\", new=AsyncMock(return_value={\"matched\": 0, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0})):\n        result = pipeline.run_sync(cfg_file)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 0, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `notify.py` — notifiers + `dispatch`\n\n**Gaps**\n- Each notifier's env-var gate: not activated when var unset; activated when set.\n- Each notifier no-ops when `new` and `changed` are both empty (even with env vars set) — important, since it prevents spurious pings.\n- `notify_sms`: `_sms_body` truncation logic (`limit=8`, `\"+N more\"` line) and ASCII-only guarantee.\n- `notify_email`: SMTP auth only attempted when `SMTP_USER` set; `starttls()` always called.\n- `notify_webhook`/`notify_slack`: correct payload shape sent to `httpx.post`.\n- **`dispatch()` error isolation** — if one notifier raises, the rest still run (currently untested; this is a real resiliency guarantee worth locking in).\n- `notify_sms` raises on non-2xx (`raise_for_status()`) — verify this propagates up to `dispatch`'s try/except rather than crashing the whole run.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\nimport notify\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef make_job(**kw):\n    defaults = dict(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\")\n    defaults.update(kw)\n    return Job(**defaults)\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_without_env(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n        notify.notify_slack([make_job()], [])\n    post.assert_not_called()\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_no_jobs(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n    with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n        notify.notify_slack([], [])\n    post.assert_not_called()\n\ndef test_notify_slack_posts_when_configured_and_new_jobs(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n    with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\") as post:\n        notify.notify_slack([make_job()], [])\n    post.assert_called_once()\n    assert \"Eng\" in post.call_args.kwargs[\"json\"][\"text\"]\n\ndef test_sms_body_truncates_and_is_ascii_only():\n    jobs = [make_job(external_id=str(i), title=f\"Role {i}\") for i in range(10)]\n    body = notify._sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"+2 more\" in body\n    assert body.isascii()\n\ndef test_notify_sms_raises_on_http_error(monkeypatch):\n    for k, v in {\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\": \"sid\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\": \"tok\",\n                 \"TWILIO_FROM\": \"+1\", \"TWILIO_TO\": \"+2\"}.items():\n        monkeypatch.setenv(k, v)\n    resp = MagicMock()\n    resp.raise_for_status.side_effect = Exception(\"bad creds\")\n    with patch(\"notify.httpx.post\", return_value=resp):\n        with pytest.raises(Exception, match=\"bad creds\"):\n            notify.notify_sms([make_job()], [])\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"kaboom\")\n    boom.__name__ = \"boom\"\n    good = MagicMock(__name__=\"good\")\n    with patch(\"notify.NOTIFIERS\", [boom, good]):\n        notify.dispatch([make_job()], [])\n    good.assert_called_once()\n    assert \"kaboom\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. `fetchers.py` — the largest, most fragile module (~50% of the codebase)\n\n**This is where the real risk lives** — 15 ATS integrations, each with bespoke parsing (regex-scraped HTML, positional JSON arrays, GraphQL tokens). None are tested. Use `respx` to mock `httpx.AsyncClient` so tests run offline and deterministically.\n\n**Gaps by function:**\n- `_request`: retry-on-5xx/429, exponential backoff triggered, gives up after `retries` attempts and raises `RuntimeError`, non-retryable 4xx (e.g. 404) fails immediately without retrying.\n- `parse_greenhouse`/`parse_lever`/`parse_ashby`/`parse_smartrecruiters`/`parse_recruitee`/`parse_workable`: each has multiple optional/fallback fields (`isListed` filter in Ashby, `location` as dict-vs-flat-string in Workable/Recruitee) — each branch needs a fixture.\n- `_lever_salary`: min/max present vs absent vs only `salaryDescriptionPlain`.\n- `_extract_ds1`/`parse_google`: regex fails to match (returns `[]`), malformed JSON in the blob (`JSONDecodeError` path), missing positional indices (`IndexError` guarded by `len(j) > idx`).\n- `parse_deshaw`/`parse_twosigma`: dedup logic (`seen` set) when the same job renders multiple times; missing optional fields (no location match).\n- `fetch_twosigma`/`fetch_optiver`/`fetch_google`/`fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_netflix`/`fetch_amazon`: pagination stop condition (empty page ends loop), `max_pages` safety cap actually enforced, dedup across pages via `seen`.\n- `fetch_workday`: pagination via `total`/`offset`, the `offset > 5000` safety cap.\n- `fetch_meta`: token-scrape failure (regex doesn't match → empty tokens still sent), `\"for (;;);\"` prefix stripping, GraphQL `errors` key raises `RuntimeError`.\n- `_amazon_posted_at`: malformed date string returns `\"\"` instead of raising.\n- `fetch_source`: unknown `ats` key raises `ValueError` with the list of known ATSes.\n- `fetch_all`: **per-source failure isolation** (one source raising doesn't kill the whole batch — currently only tested implicitly, never explicitly), `concurrency` semaphore actually limits parallelism, client lifecycle (`owns_client` — closes only self-created clients, not caller-supplied ones).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers.py\nimport json\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nimport respx\nfrom fetchers import (\n    parse_greenhouse, parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby, parse_workable,\n    _extract_ds1, parse_google, parse_deshaw, parse_twosigma,\n    _amazon_posted_at, parse_amazon, fetch_source, fetch_all, _request, FETCHERS,\n)\n\n# --- pure parser tests (no network) -----------------------------------------\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_basic():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"Eng\", \"absolute_url\": \"u\",\n                       \"location\": {\"name\": \"NYC\"}, \"departments\": [{\"name\": \"Infra\"}],\n                       \"updated_at\": \"2026-01-01T00:00:00Z\"}]}\n    jobs = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1 and jobs[0].location == \"NYC\" and jobs[0].department == \"Infra\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_prefers_min_max_over_description():\n    j = {\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"},\n         \"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"ignored\"}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"USD 100,000–150,000\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_falls_back_to_description():\n    assert _lever_salary({\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}) == \"Competitive\"\n\ndef test_parse_ashby_skips_unlisted_jobs():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"isListed\": False, \"title\": \"Hidden\"},\n                     {\"id\": \"2\", \"isListed\": True, \"title\": \"Visible\"}]}\n    jobs = parse_ashby(\"x\", data)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1 and jobs[0].title == \"Visible\"\n\ndef test_parse_workable_handles_dict_and_flat_location():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [\n        {\"shortcode\": \"a\", \"title\": \"T1\", \"location\": {\"location_str\": \"Remote\"}},\n        {\"shortcode\": \"b\", \"title\": \"T2\", \"city\": \"Austin\", \"state\": \"TX\", \"country\": \"US\"},\n    ]}\n    jobs = parse_workable(\"x\", data)\n    assert jobs[0].location == \"Remote\"\n    assert jobs[1].location == \"Austin, TX, US\"\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_returns_empty_on_no_match():\n    assert _extract_ds1(\"<html>no data here</html>\") == []\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_returns_empty_on_malformed_json():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', data:[not valid json], sideChannel\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []\n\ndef test_parse_google_handles_short_arrays_defensively():\n    # missing indices 9, 12-14 shouldn't raise\n    jobs = parse_google(\"google\", [[\"123\", \"Title\"]])\n    assert jobs[0].external_id == \"123\" and jobs[0].location == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_deshaw_dedups_repeated_cards():\n    html = ('data-job-id=\"1\" class=\"job-display-name\">Engineer<'\n            'data-job-id=\"1\" class=\"job-display-name\">Engineer<')\n    jobs = parse_deshaw(\"deshaw\", html)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_malformed_returns_empty():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"garbage\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_valid():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises():\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        import asyncio\n        asyncio.run(fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"bogus\"}))\n\n# --- network-mocked tests (respx) -------------------------------------------\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds():\n    route = respx.get(\"https://x/y\")\n    route.side_effect = [httpx.Response(503), httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})]\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://x/y\", retries=3)\n    assert r.status_code == 200\n    assert route.call_count == 2\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_request_gives_up_after_max_retries():\n    respx.get(\"https://x/y\").mock(return_value=httpx.Response(500))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"failed to fetch\"):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x/y\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_per_source_failures(capsys):\n    respx.get(\"https://boards-api.greenhouse.io/v1/boards/good/jobs\").mock(\n        return_value=httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": []}))\n    respx.get(\"https://boards-api.greenhouse.io/v1/boards/bad/jobs\").mock(\n        return_value=httpx.Response(500))\n    sources = [{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"good\"},\n               {\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"bad\"}]\n    jobs = await fetch_all(sources, concurrency=2)\n    assert jobs == []  # both empty, but crucially it didn't raise\n    assert \"failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\n@respx.mock\nasync def test_fetch_optiver_pagination_stops_on_empty_page():\n    respx.get(\"https://www.optiver.com/en/api/v1/jobs\").mock(side_effect=[\n        httpx.Response(200, json={\"items\": [{\"href\": \"/join-us/jobs/a\", \"title\": \"A\"}]}),\n        httpx.Response(200, json={\"items\": []}),\n    ])\n    from fetchers import fetch_optiver\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        jobs = await fetch_optiver(client, {\"company\": \"optiver\"})\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py` — CLI subcommands (`db-new`, `db-mark`, `pdf-render`) + `run_claude`\n\n**Gaps — entirely untested, and this is where the \"watermark\" dedup logic (a subtle invariant) lives.**\n- `cmd_db_new`: first-run (no marker) uses `since_days` window; group-boundary truncation (`watermark` must land on a `first_seen` boundary, never mid-group) — this is the trickiest bit of logic in the file and has zero coverage.\n- `cmd_db_mark`: invalid ISO string returns exit code 2 and doesn't touch the DB; `--now` vs explicit watermark; neither given → exit 2.\n- `_normalize_ats`: replacements skip `<style>`/`<script>` contents and tag attributes, only touch body text; counts dict accumulates per-label.\n- `cmd_pdf_render`: missing input file → exit 2; Chrome not found → `sys.exit`; Chrome produces non-PDF output → exit 1 with stderr surfaced.\n- `main()` arg-routing: bare `agent.py` → interactive; `agent.py scan` → headless; `agent.py scan -i` → interactive; mode words stop at first flag.\n- `run_claude`: `os.execvp` called for interactive (need to mock — never actually exec in test), `subprocess.call` for headless with the right flags.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent.py\nimport json\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nimport agent\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\n\ndef test_cmd_db_new_first_run_uses_since_days_window(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as store:\n        store.diff([Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")])\n    agent.cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--since-days\", \"1\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"first_run\"] is True\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 1\n\ndef test_cmd_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary_not_mid_group(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    db = tmp_path / \"jobs.db\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {db}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    with Store(db) as store:\n        jobs = [Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=str(i), title=\"T\", url=\"u\")\n                for i in range(3)]\n        store.diff(jobs)  # all share one first_seen timestamp (one group)\n    agent.cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--limit\", \"2\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    # limit=2 can't split the 3-job group -> keeps 0 from this group, truncated=True\n    assert out[\"truncated\"] is True\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 0\n\ndef test_cmd_db_mark_rejects_non_iso_watermark(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    rc = agent.cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-date\", \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n    assert \"not an ISO timestamp\" in capsys.readouterr().err\n\ndef test_cmd_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(tmp_path, capsys):\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"db: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\nsources: []\\n\")\n    rc = agent.cmd_db_mark([\"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_skips_style_and_script_blocks():\n    html = \"<style>.x::before{content:'\\u2014'}</style><p>em\\u2014dash</p><script>var x='\\u2014';</script>\"\n    out, counts = agent._normalize_ats(html)\n    assert \"content:'\\u2014'\" in out          # untouched inside <style>\n    assert \"var x='\\u2014'\" in out            # untouched inside <script>\n    assert \"em-dash\" in out                   # replaced in body text\n    assert counts.get(\"em-dash\") == 1\n\ndef test_cmd_pdf_render_missing_input_file(tmp_path, capsys):\n    rc = agent.cmd_pdf_render([str(tmp_path / \"missing.html\")])\n    assert rc == 2\n    assert \"no such file\" in capsys.readouterr().err\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"argv,expected_interactive,expected_mode_words\", [\n    ([], True, []),\n    ([\"scan\"], False, [\"scan\"]),\n    ([\"scan\", \"-i\"], True, [\"scan\"]),\n    ([\"scan\", \"--foo\", \"bar\"], False, [\"scan\"]),\n])\ndef test_main_routing(argv, expected_interactive, expected_mode_words, monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"agent.py\", *argv])\n    with patch(\"agent.run_claude\") as rc:\n        rc.return_value = 0\n        agent.main()\n    called_words, called_interactive, _ = rc.call_args[0]\n    assert called_interactive is expected_interactive\n    assert called_words == expected_mode_words\n```\n\n---\n\n### 8. `cli.py`\n\n**Gaps**\n- `argparse` defaults (`--config` defaults to `sources.yaml`, `--dry-run` defaults to `False`).\n- `main()` passes parsed args through to `run_sync` correctly.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_cli.py\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nimport cli\n\ndef test_main_passes_config_and_dry_run_flag(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"cli.py\", \"-c\", \"custom.yaml\", \"--dry-run\"])\n    with patch(\"cli.run_sync\") as run_sync:\n        cli.main()\n    run_sync.assert_called_once_with(\"custom.yaml\", dry_run=True)\n\ndef test_main_defaults(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"cli.py\"])\n    with patch(\"cli.run_sync\") as run_sync:\n        cli.main()\n    run_sync.assert_called_once_with(\"sources.yaml\", dry_run=False)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Integration gaps (no unit test can cover these alone)\n\n1. **End-to-end pipeline run**: real `sources.yaml` → `fetch_all` (mocked at the HTTP layer via `respx`) → `filter_jobs` → `Store.diff` on a real temp SQLite file → `dispatch` (notifiers mocked) → assert final counts. None of this crosses module boundaries today.\n2. **`agent.py db-new` / `db-mark` cycle**: run a pipeline, dump `db-new`, mark with the returned `watermark`, dump `db-new` again and confirm the previously-dumped jobs don't reappear (the exact invariant the group-boundary truncation code exists to protect).\n3. **Store migration on a real legacy DB file** created by an older schema, then run a full pipeline against it.\n4. **Notifier fan-out with a real `dispatch()` call and multiple env vars set simultaneously** (Slack + webhook + SMS all configured) verifying all fire independently.\n\n### Priority order to close gaps\n1. `store.py` (data-integrity risk, diff/migration untested) and `fetchers.py` retry/pagination/parsing (the biggest surface, highest fragility — noted in the code's own comments about Meta's rotating doc_id and Google's positional indices).\n2. `agent.py`'s `cmd_db_new` truncation logic (subtle correctness bug risk on the \"did we skip jobs\" invariant).\n3. `filters.py`/`models.py` (small, pure, cheap to cover fully).\n4. `notify.py`/`pipeline.py`/`cli.py` (mostly glue, but `dispatch` error isolation is worth locking in).\n",
