      {
        "title": "6. `fetchers.py` — the largest, most fragile module (~50% of the codebase)",
        "content": "\n**This is where the real risk lives** — 15 ATS integrations, each with bespoke parsing (regex-scraped HTML, positional JSON arrays, GraphQL tokens). None are tested. Use `respx` to mock `httpx.AsyncClient` so tests run offline and deterministically.\n\n**Gaps by function:**\n- `_request`: retry-on-5xx/429, exponential backoff triggered, gives up after `retries` attempts and raises `RuntimeError`, non-retryable 4xx (e.g. 404) fails immediately without retrying.\n- `parse_greenhouse`/`parse_lever`/`parse_ashby`/`parse_smartrecruiters`/`parse_recruitee`/`parse_workable`: each has multiple optional/fallback fields (`isListed` filter in Ashby, `location` as dict-vs-flat-string in Workable/Recruitee) — each branch needs a fixture.\n- `_lever_salary`: min/max present vs absent vs only `salaryDescriptionPlain`.\n- `_extract_ds1`/`parse_google`: regex fails to match (returns `[]`), malformed JSON in the blob (`JSONDecodeError` path), missing positional indices (`IndexError` guarded by `len(j) > idx`).\n- `parse_deshaw`/`parse_twosigma`: dedup logic (`seen` set) when the same job renders multiple times; missing optional fields (no location match).\n- `fetch_twosigma`/`fetch_optiver`/`fetch_google`/`fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_netflix`/`fetch_amazon`: pagination stop condition (empty page ends loop), `max_pages` safety cap actually enforced, dedup across pages via `seen`.\n- `fetch_workday`: pagination via `total`/`offset`, the `offset > 5000` safety cap.\n- `fetch_meta`: token-scrape failure (regex doesn't match → empty tokens still sent), `\"for (;;);\"` prefix stripping, GraphQL `errors` key raises `RuntimeError`.\n- `_amazon_posted_at`: malformed date string returns `\"\"` instead of raising.\n- `fetch_source`: unknown `ats` key raises `ValueError` with the list of known ATSes.\n- `fetch_all`: **per-source failure isolation** (one source raising doesn't kill the whole batch — currently only tested implicitly, never explicitly), `concurrency` semaphore actually limits parallelism, client lifecycle (`owns_client` — closes only self-created clients, not caller-supplied ones).\n\n```python\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
